    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-04T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-04T16:00:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1955</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-04T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 4, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your 140, May 2, 6 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d245fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1918Russiav01#pg_519">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                            519</ref>.</note> The Department is considering carefully your
                    suggestion as to intervention in Siberia and would be pleased to have you
                    suggest in more concrete form a plan of action, taking into consideration the
                    fact that the military forces to be employed would of necessity be almost wholly
                    Japanese on account of the lack of shipping in the Pacific, which prevents our
                    sending troops at present.</p>
                <p>I would also be pleased to have your views as to the military advantage to be
                    gained by an advance into Siberia which could not, on account of the great
                    distances, extend much if any beyond Irkutsk, and also as to the effect upon the
                    attitude of the people of European Russia if the Japanese entered Siberia with
                    the approval and support of this country and the Allies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
